		<div id="comment_body_65325759"><p><div class="quote"><p>First, most of these problems are about general remote communication problems,  but the article is jumping to the conclusion that a wireless LAN is the only possible fix. Almost all the problems addressed in the article could be addressed with an email terminal.</p><p>Second, the article both says that there is WLAN on these ships, but the staff is "not allowed to use" it - while also claiming that the owners "don&#226;(TM)t want to put Wi-Fi on their ships". So which is it?</p></div><p>An e-mail terminal would get monitored by corporate...as soon as the word "union" or "organize" gets typed, expect a sudden loss of internet.  Corporate overlords who abuse migrants can't be trusted to not abuse their rights.  Open and un-monitored Wi-Fi is the only reasonable solution.  If these corporations are afraid of that, it makes you wonder what they're hiding.  It's a fishing vessel, not a nuclear launch site.  The only motivation for secrecy is to hide illegal labor abuses.  <br> <br>  Deep sea fishing is<span class="substr"> </span></p></div>
	</div>

	<div class="commentSub" id="comment_sub_65325759">

</div>
</div>

<div id="replyto_65325759"></div>

<ul id="group_65325759">
	<li id="hiddens_65325759" class="hide"></li>
</ul>

